, "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Inflation reduces the purchasing power of your future returns. If a stock grows by 8% but inflation is 3%, your real rate of return is roughly 5%. While some calculators show nominal numbers, you should always mentally discount future values by historical inflation averages."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why is regular contribution so important in stock investing?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Regular contributions (often called dollar-cost averaging) help smooth out market volatility and dramatically accelerate portfolio growth over time. By consistently adding capital, you accumulate more shares during market dips, which lowers your average cost basis."}}]}]};
---

<SiteLayout
